thread.title: CNU junior Sutton, from Jamestown High, reaches volleyball milestone
thread.title_full: CNU junior Sutton, from Jamestown High, reaches volleyball milestone

title: CNU junior Sutton, from Jamestown High, reaches volleyball milestone
text:
CNU junior Sutton, from Jamestown High, reaches volleyball milestone Compiled by Daily Press 
COLLEGES: 
Women’s volleyball: 
After being named the Capital Athletic Conference Player of the Week for the second time this season, junior Briana Sutton of Christopher Newport had 19 kills — including the 1,000th of her career — to spark a 25-27, 25-12, 25-23, 25-17 win at Gallaudet. 
Rachel Conway had 48 assists, Rachel Close had 23 digs and Ashley Rock had seven blocks for CNU (23-2), the nation's fifth-ranked Division III team. The Bison fell to 17-9. 
To earn the award, Sutton -- a Jamestown High product -- posted a pair of double-doubles in a 4-0 week that included a trio of CAC victories. 
Football: 
Virginia State sophomore Trenton Cannon, a Kecoughtan High graduate, was named the Central Intercollegiate Athletic Association Offensive Back of the Week. He ran for a season-high 184 yards on 12 carries and all three of VSU’s touchdowns in a 22-19 loss to Bowie State. ... 
Elizabeth City State junior Brian Wells was named the CIAA Offensive Lineman of the Week, while teammate Stephen Williams was honored as Linebacker of the Week. Wells sparked ECSU to 500 yards of offense and three rushing touchdowns. Williams had 16 tackles and leads the CIAA in that category. ... 
Apprentice School sophomore quarterback Brenden O'Neil was named the United States Collegiate Athletic Association Offensive Player of the Week. 
O'Neil, an electrician apprentice from Virginia Beach, led the Builders to a 44-13 victory over USCAA member Alfred State in New York. O'Neil rushed for 131 yards on 16 carries, averaging 8.2 yards per carry, and got into the end zone twice. 
Men’s soccer: 
Host William and Mary beat UNC Asheville 4-2 on goals by William Eskay, Jackson Eskay, Ryder Bell and Marcel Berry. The Tribe led 3-0 just 20:24 into the game. ... 
Charlotte dominated Virginia Tech 5-0. 
Women’s soccer: 
CNU (11-3-1) entered the d3soccer.com poll at No. 25. ... 
Virginia senior Makenzy Doniak was named an Atlantic Coast Conference Co-Offensive Player of the Week. Her goal and assist in the No. 2 Cavaliers’ 4-2 win at Boston College last weekend gave her 138 career points. That enabled Doniak to share the U.Va. record set by Angela Hucles, who grew up in Virginia Beach, in 1999. 
Men’s basketball: 
Dayton was picked first in the Atlantic 10 poll, while VCU was tabbed fifth and Richmond sixth. 
Women’s golf: 
Hampton sophomore Britney Smith won the weekend Delaware State Hornet Fall Invitational in Dover. 
She shot an 11-over-par 157 for 36 holes to tie Quinnipiac’s Luciana Tobia, then parred the first playoff hole to win the medal. Tobia double-bogeyed the 18th hole. ... 
Old Dominion placed second to tournament host Campbell in the 15-team Fighting Camel Classic in Buies Creek, N.C. The Camels, ranked 54th nationally, shot 38-over-par 902 for three rounds, while ODU was at 919 and third-place Northern Arizona at 927. 
Charlotte LaCorte led ODU by tying for seventh among 84 golfers. She finished with an even-par 72 for a 12-over 228, and teammate Sana Tufail tied for 10th at 230. 
Men’s tennis: 
Virginia Tech’s Joao Monteiro won the Intercollegiate Tennis Association Atlantic Regional singles title 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) over Old Dominion’s Adam Moundir in Blacksburg. But Moundir and Aziz Kijametovic bounced back in the doubles final to edge the Hokies’ Amerigo Contini and Edoardo Tessaro 2-6, 6-4, 1-0 (10-8). 
The champions earned berths in the national indoor championships.Nov. 12-15 at Flushing Meadows, N.Y. 
Field hockey: 
Temple (4-12, 1-2 Big East) snapped an eight-game losing streak with a 1-0 victory at No. 12 Old Dominion, despite being outshot 21-4 by the Monarchs (8-6, 1-2). 
Sarah Deck’s seventh goal of the season, off a penalty corner, came at the 17:05 mark of the first half. It was ODU’s third consecutive 1-0 loss. 
Men’s cross country: 
CNU sophomore Grayson Reid was named the CAC Men’s Cross Country Athlete of the Week for the second straight week. 
He led the Captains with an 8-kilometer time of 25:47 in the CNU Invitational at Lee Hall Mansion — second among Division III competitors and fifth among all entrants.
